node.text:
If all of your debts are paid in full and the accounts are closed, you'll have what's called an "indeterminable" credit score after about 6 months. Then, you'll be able to do what's called "manual underwriting" to buy a home. All that means is that the mortgage company will do what banks used to do all the time when someone bought a home. They'll actually review your finances to check out whether or not you're in a position to pay back the loan.

A mortgage is the only type of debt, I'm okay with. Just make sure that the payment is no more than 25% of your take-home pay on no more than a 15-year mortgage at a fixed rate. I want your house to be a financial blessing in your life, not a financial curse.

You CAN have financial peace. You just need to take your time and do the math to make sure things are done right.

Thanks to Dr. @johndelony for joining me on this call. 

#debtfreecommunity 
#mortgage

node.text:
There's an addictive thrill that can come with the risk on these sorts of things. Although a lot of people are having a lot of fun with this right now, it's important to not confuse a get-rich-quick scenario with an actual, proven wealth-building plan. Just because a few people won the lottery one time does NOT make it an investment strategy that you should use. If you're debt-free with a full emergency fund, and you want to use some fun/entertainment money that you've budgeted for to play around with these things, I'm not gonna get mad at you, but I don't recommend it… and I certainly don't do this myself. If you REALLY want to play around with single stocks, just make sure that no more than 10% of your net worth is tied up in them. This is to ensure that things don't go overboard to the point that it can actually impact your net worth in a negative way if and when things go south. 

Reminder: I only recommend investing in mutual funds and real estate that's paid for in full. 

#debtfreecommunity

Great conversation with @kencoleman.

Budgeting isn't easy at first, but it's worth it. You've got to push through a few months to learn how to get your budget right. It's only when the pain of where you are exceeds the pain of making the change that you will actually decide to CHANGE. The struggle at the beginning is part of the learning process.

Push through— you'll get there. You can do this! 💪

#debtfreecommunity

node.text:
Awesome. Way to go, you guys! Thanks for coordinating a Financial Peace University class too! 

#repost @brettwright55

D E B T F R E E

(Long Post 😬)

This path was by no means easy nor quick but I can now say that every second was worth it! From getting a second job at Publix, to meal planning, cutting out subscriptions, only shopping for necessities…it was all worth to stand where we are today! There’s no words to describe the feeling lifted off your shoulders when you are debt free.

There’s no quick & easy formula. It was done through hard work, patience, discipline, setting goals, teamwork, and most importantly God’s provision. The best part of this journey is that it’s so much more than financial status but the growth we experienced!

•We grew closer to God by trusting him with EVERY penny of our finances.

•We grew closer together by working as a team on our budget & trusting each other through this journey.

•We grew in the areas we needed to such as patience, discipline, & knowledge about finances.

I say all that to say if we can do it, YOU CAN TOO! That’s why we are beyond excited to lead a “Financial Peace University” life group this fall at River of Life! We would love for you to join! Sign up at rolhamilton.churchcenter.com/groups

“Live like no else so that you can live like no else.”

#debtfreecommunity
#debtfreescream

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dave Ramsey on September 05, 2021. May be a Twitter screenshot of 1 person and text that says 'Dave Ramsey @DaveRamsey You know what a new car is after you've had it fo a year? A used car.'.

node.text:
A new car goes down in value like a rock. Unless you have a $1 Million net worth, don't purchase a new car. You can buy a reliable used car for a fraction of the new car price. Be smart about this, and pay CASH. Your future is too valuable to waste your money on stupid car payments. 

#debtfreecommunity

node.text:
WOW. $247,000 PAID OFF! You did it! SO proud of you. 🎉

#repost @elisedds

19 months ago I decided to do something unordinary. I challenged myself to pay off my student loans and car as quickly as possible. Some people thought I was nuts, but others cheered me on until I completed this marathon, or sprint, however you choose to perceive it. This came with extreme sacrifices such as not partaking in most weekend activities, no vacations or shopping for anything other than basic necessities. This journey sucked, but it taught me a lesson in contentment, perseverance, grit and determination.

I want to thank my amazing fiancé, Nnamdi, for being the most patient and understanding person as I took on this insane journey. It all started because of one car ride home from London with you we caught an episode of @daveramsey and I was inspired to change our family tree and legacy we’ll leave behind. From that day forward, I listened to @daveramsey and @anthonyoneal on my commute home from work to remain motivated. To God all the glory! I can finally say I’M DEBT FREEEEE!!!!!!🎉

#debtfree #livelikenooneelse #freedom
#debtfreecommunity #debtfreescream

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dave Ramsey on September 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Notes 5 Practical Ways to Save Money 1. Cut down on your grocery budget Plan out meals and try online pickup to avoid impulse buys. 2. Pack your lunch The average household spend $294 each month on food outside the home. 3. Sell all that stuff you don't need Declutter your house and you'll have more money and space. 4. Try a spending freeze Don't buy any nonessential items for a week-or even a month. 5. Say goodbye to debt Debt robs you of your income. Google "debt snowball method" for the fastest way to pay off debt.'.

node.text:
Solid advice from my team. Remember, winning with money is about what you DO with your money, not as much about the amount you make. Every bit of progress counts! 

#repost @ramsey.solutions

We'd all love to save more money, but how do you actually start? You just gotta do it!
 
For sure, it's not easy. But you’ll only start saving money when you learn healthy money habits and let your future needs be more important than your current wants—when you make saving money a priority.
 
So let's get started! What ideas would you add to this list?

#debtfreecommunity

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dave Ramsey on September 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Notes Federal student loan relief was extended again last month. But, just because you aren't required to make payments at the moment doesn't mean you shouldn't. If you CAN make the payments, this is the best time to keep making them. Each dollar you put toward your federal student loans right now goes straight to your principal balance which helps you pay it off so much faster!'.

node.text:
If you're working the debt snowball, and it's time to tackle your student debt, go for it. Put every extra penny you have toward those loans! Except for your $1,000 emergency fund, of course.

For some people, refinancing student loans to get a lower interest rate could be a great option to help pay them off even faster.

🔗Click the link in my profile to get in touch with the only company I trust to help you see if refinancing could be a good option for you.

#debtfreecommunity 
#studentloans

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dave Ramsey on September 02, 2021. May be a Twitter screenshot of 1 person and text that says 'Dave Ramsey @DaveRamsey 1/3 of millionaires NEVER made six figures in any single year of their career. What you actually do with the money you make matters more than the amount of money you make. There are plenty of people making a LOT of money who live paycheck to paycheck.'.

node.text:
It IS possible to become a millionaire, and you don't have to make a ton of money to do it. Use a budget, live on less than you make, stay out of debt, and invest steadily. Work the 7 Baby Steps to get there. It's not a flashy, get-rich-quick plan. It's a plan that WORKS. 

#debtfreecommunity 
#millionaire

#repost @deidrenoel_

“Live like no one else, so you can live like no one else” -Dave Ramsey

85k of school loans gone in 21 months!!! After LOTS of overtime, budgeting, and saying “no”, we are SOOOO EXCITED TO BE DEBT FREE!! Cole and I participated in FPU during college and quickly realized this was something we wanted to bring into our marriage! Initially, our goal was to pay off our loans in the first two years of marriage, but we made our last payment 11 days after our first anniversary!!!!👏🏻 We are super thankful for our friends and family who were so encouraging and motivating during this journey!!!
